{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":17017,"record_hash":"sha256:463da8c2992b68405108db089baa56c6a08194c068e153f7f081e6ad6cc92587","timestamp":"2026-05-09T20:13:39.758Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 478ef9\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 733\nOutput:\n  naming, and idiomatic Rust.\n- **Test reviewer**: check whether tests protect behavior and whether any tests\n  are brittle implementation mirrors.\n\nOptional subagents:\n\n- **Security/privacy reviewer**, when redaction or transcript storage changed.\n- **Performance reviewer**, when parsing, redaction, or GitMeta read/write loops\n  changed.\n\nDo not ask subagents to rewrite files. Their output should be a short list of\nhigh-signal findings with file/line references when possible.\n\n### Step 3. Triage Findings\n\nThe main agent should merge subagent feedback into three buckets:\n\n- **Fix now**: behavior risk, privacy risk, confusing boundary, or easy\n  simplification.\n- **Document only**: useful future concern but not POC-sized.\n- **Ignore**: speculative architecture, taste-only renames, or changes that make\n  the POC larger.\n\nPrefer deleting or renaming over introducing new abstractions. If a finding\nrequires a new framework, it is probably not a cleanup finding.\n\n### Step 4. Make Small Behavior-Preserving Edits\n\nEdit in small groups:\n\n1. deletion/inlining\n2. naming\n3. visibility tightening\n4. comment cleanup\n5. test cleanup\n\nRun `cargo fmt` after edits. Avoid mixing a behavior fix with broad cleanup\nunless the behavior fix is tiny and directly discovered by the cleanup.\n\n### Step 5. Run Verification\n\nRun:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p but-agentlog\ncargo check -p but --features agentlog\ncargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\ncargo machete\n```\n\nIf dependencies did not change, `cargo machete` is still cheap and catches\ncleanup leftovers.\n\n### Step 6. Optional Second Review\n\nAfter edits, spawn one or two fresh subagents only if the diff is non-trivial.\n\nGood second-pass prompts:\n\n- \"Review only the cleanup diff. Did behavior accidentally change?\"\n- \"Look for new complexity introduced by the cleanup.\"\n- \"Check whether any tests became weaker or more implementation-coupled.\"\n\nAvoid repeating the full four-subagent review unless the cleanup touched many\nmodules. Re-review has diminishing returns.\n\n### Step 7. Summarize The Result\n\nThe final summary should say:\n\n- what was removed or clarified\n- whether behavior changed\n- what validation ran\n- any remaining deliberate POC tradeoffs\n\nDo not claim the crate is now \"future-proof.\" The point is that it is easier to\nchange later because it is smaller and clearer now.\n\n## Cursor Note\n\nDo not force Cursor into the current JSONL parser path. Cursor's normal chat\nhistory is local SQLite, and its documented portable flow is Markdown export.\nThat deserves a separate design pass later.\n\n## Validation Habit\n\nBefore and after cleanup, run the narrow checks:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p but-agentlog\ncargo check -p but --features agentlog\ncargo clippy -p but-agentlog --all-targets --no-deps\ncargo machete\n```\n\nFor behavior-neutral cleanup, the best result is boring: smaller code, clearer\nnames, and the same tests passing.\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-09T20:13:39.758Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}